WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.640
Hello everyone, and welcome to this afternoon's webinar.

00:00:08.640 --> 00:00:13.280
My name is Greg Wilson, I work for RStudio on the education team, and we've put this

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:18.080
one together to help everybody who is finding themselves moving their teaching online at

00:00:18.080 --> 00:00:19.080
short notice.

00:00:19.080 --> 00:00:23.559
I'd like to thank Robert and Curtis for setting up all of the mechanics for this.

00:00:23.559 --> 00:00:27.420
And there is a question tab in GoToWebinar.

00:00:27.420 --> 00:00:31.340
Please throw questions into it at any time during the presentation, we'll field some

00:00:31.340 --> 00:00:35.380
of them during the call, and we'll gather up the rest at the end.

00:00:35.380 --> 00:00:40.740
All right, let's get rolling because it's a big world in a short day.

00:00:40.740 --> 00:00:47.779
So you all had plans, you all had some idea of how you were going to teach a course this

00:00:47.779 --> 00:00:51.939
semester, how you were going to deliver that training workshop, and now all of a sudden

00:00:51.939 --> 00:00:55.380
you find yourself in an off-road vehicle at night.

00:00:55.380 --> 00:01:00.619
We've all of us been thrown off our plans in the last couple of weeks, and quite reasonably

00:01:00.619 --> 00:01:05.180
a lot of us are afraid that things are going to crash out bad.

00:01:05.180 --> 00:01:07.139
We're here to help.

00:01:07.139 --> 00:01:12.620
What we're going to do in the next 45 minutes is give you a few tips that we hope will help

00:01:12.620 --> 00:01:18.580
you move your teaching online without crashing.

00:01:18.580 --> 00:01:23.419
It's not the best you could possibly do, it's what you can do in a hurry with the tools

00:01:23.419 --> 00:01:29.080
you've got and the time you have, because like your learners, you're probably now wrestling

00:01:29.080 --> 00:01:33.940
with a whole bunch of issues around looking after kids or elderly parents, travel plans

00:01:33.940 --> 00:01:39.860
being canceled, everybody and their cousin being on bandwidth at the same time.

00:01:39.860 --> 00:01:42.699
We're hoping that these tips will help you get through that.

00:01:42.699 --> 00:01:48.139
Now this is the persona I had in mind when I developed this deck.

00:01:48.139 --> 00:01:51.739
She's pre-tenure faculty, also teaches in industry.

00:01:51.739 --> 00:01:54.580
She's comfortable using modern tools.

00:01:54.580 --> 00:01:57.019
She FaceTimes with her partner all the time.

00:01:57.019 --> 00:02:01.699
She struggles a bit with her school's learning management system, but that's Blackboard's

00:02:01.699 --> 00:02:03.260
fault, that's not hers.

00:02:03.260 --> 00:02:07.620
And now she's got to move a class of 80 people online in a week so that they can finish semester

00:02:07.620 --> 00:02:09.080
more or less on time.

00:02:09.080 --> 00:02:12.759
And she's also got a couple of workshops that she signed contracts for.

00:02:12.759 --> 00:02:15.380
She really doesn't want to have to cancel out of those.

00:02:15.380 --> 00:02:19.979
And above all of this, she is afraid that whatever happens in the next few weeks is

00:02:19.979 --> 00:02:24.339
just going to suck a lot of time away from research, and she's a year away from applying

00:02:24.339 --> 00:02:25.339
for tenure.

00:02:25.339 --> 00:02:30.520
And I put this concept map together in order to figure out what I was going to cover.

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:34.820
I wound up covering more than this, so I'm going to skip and go to the first and most

00:02:34.820 --> 00:02:35.820
important rule.

00:02:35.820 --> 00:02:39.979
And if you take one thing away from today's talk, I want it to be this, don't change what

00:02:39.979 --> 00:02:40.979
you don't have to.

00:02:41.979 --> 00:02:45.779
Now, there's an old saying, if you're going on a long walk, you wear old shoes.

00:02:45.779 --> 00:02:48.580
You don't wear new shoes if you've got a long way to go.

00:02:48.580 --> 00:02:53.460
Please don't try to change 19 different things about your class, because you've heard that

00:02:53.460 --> 00:02:57.619
the right way to teach online is to use X or do Y.

00:02:57.619 --> 00:03:03.779
Right now, running late, running without extra resources, what we want to look for is the

00:03:03.779 --> 00:03:09.940
smallest possible changes we can make, and that's what I'm going to be focusing on.

00:03:09.940 --> 00:03:14.059
The second rule, and this one comes from Elizabeth Wicks at the University of Illinois,

00:03:14.059 --> 00:03:16.380
please don't make assumptions.

00:03:16.380 --> 00:03:19.699
Please ask your learners, your students, your colleagues.

00:03:19.699 --> 00:03:23.360
They aren't going to have the same bandwidth that you have.

00:03:23.360 --> 00:03:25.660
Their network might not be as reliable.

00:03:25.660 --> 00:03:29.699
Their computer at home might be a six-year-old hand-me-down, because they're no longer at

00:03:29.699 --> 00:03:31.020
the university.

00:03:31.020 --> 00:03:36.020
In a corporate environment, it might be the very first time they've had to use stuff over

00:03:36.020 --> 00:03:39.740
a VPN, because they're used to going into the office.

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:45.860
They may not have the attention span they used to, because of all of these pandemic-induced

00:03:45.860 --> 00:03:46.860
distractions.

00:03:46.860 --> 00:03:50.460
So, rule number two, go and ask them.

00:03:50.460 --> 00:03:54.820
Nobody will ever be offended if you say, what kind of device are you on?

00:03:54.820 --> 00:03:59.020
How much time do you realistically have?

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:05.600
The next recommendation I've got is, please don't try to be or to beat the kind of recorded

00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:11.880
video you see in polished, produced courses on sites like edX.

00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:18.399
It takes a lot of time to edit up even a simple video, and it takes a lot of time to learn

00:04:18.399 --> 00:04:21.359
the tools you use for editing those videos.

00:04:21.359 --> 00:04:24.279
You probably don't have that time right now.

00:04:24.279 --> 00:04:27.559
I'm not saying that recorded video doesn't have its place.

00:04:27.559 --> 00:04:31.640
We're going to record this webinar and make it available to people.

00:04:31.640 --> 00:04:38.359
But right now, I think in the short run, your best bet is to try to use things interactively

00:04:38.359 --> 00:04:44.920
and worry about recording and editing and publishing video later.

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:49.279
If you're going to ignore my advice and go ahead and start doing it, there's a really

00:04:49.279 --> 00:04:55.239
good paper from 2009 by Chen and Rab called A Pattern Language for Screencasting.

00:04:55.239 --> 00:05:03.399
They take a lot of apparently straightforward ideas and organize them in a sensible way.

00:05:03.399 --> 00:05:06.040
Their concept map is up here on the screen.

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:11.079
There's just a whole bunch of good tips here about what makes for a good screencast, what

00:05:11.079 --> 00:05:16.000
makes for a good online video, and how the parts fit together so you know what not to

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.799
do or what not to venture into.

00:05:18.799 --> 00:05:22.899
All of these slides, by the way, are going to be available after the talk.

00:05:22.899 --> 00:05:25.820
So if you haven't copied down that URL, don't worry.

00:05:25.820 --> 00:05:29.459
You'll be able to find it later.

00:05:29.459 --> 00:05:34.700
Next thing I'm going to say is the mistakes are the pedagogy.

00:05:34.700 --> 00:05:40.339
Depending on whose numbers you trust, a professional programmer spends 20% to 60% of their time

00:05:40.339 --> 00:05:41.339
debugging.

00:05:41.339 --> 00:05:48.079
A novice spends 80% to 95% of their time debugging because they're a novice.

00:05:48.079 --> 00:05:51.959
The same is going to be true in most areas.

00:05:51.959 --> 00:05:57.040
So please don't worry about making mistakes in front of your learners when you're teaching

00:05:57.040 --> 00:06:02.000
online for the first or the second or the third time because every time you make a mistake

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:07.920
and then say, oh, this is wrong, here's how I can tell, here's how I figured out how to

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:13.799
fix it, and here's how I can tell it's been fixed, they will have learned something valuable.

00:06:13.799 --> 00:06:18.640
This comes back to the larger point that when you're teaching online interactively,

00:06:18.640 --> 00:06:23.660
when you're doing what I'm doing right now, you learn the song but then you improvise

00:06:23.660 --> 00:06:25.880
over it.

00:06:25.880 --> 00:06:27.239
I've got a slide deck.

00:06:27.239 --> 00:06:28.559
It has speaker's notes.

00:06:28.559 --> 00:06:32.320
I'm really glad that I prepped all of that because it got me to think through the things

00:06:32.320 --> 00:06:34.119
I'm going to say.

00:06:34.119 --> 00:06:39.239
But now what I'm actually saying on any given day is going to be partly improvised.

00:06:39.239 --> 00:06:42.079
It's going to depend on the feedback that I'm getting from my audience.

00:06:42.079 --> 00:06:47.640
It's going to depend on thoughts that I have now that I'm presenting, and that's okay.

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:52.239
The better you know your material, the more comfortable you will be improvising, but don't

00:06:52.239 --> 00:06:59.079
think that you have to stick to exactly what you planned the night before.

00:06:59.079 --> 00:07:06.959
The corollary to this is it's really, really hard to teach to a room full of empty chairs.

00:07:06.959 --> 00:07:11.399
All of us all the time are picking up social cues.

00:07:11.399 --> 00:07:16.079
We're constantly peripherally aware of whether somebody is nodding or whether they're checking

00:07:16.079 --> 00:07:17.079
their phone.

00:07:17.079 --> 00:07:21.320
Did they just yawn or are they thinking because they're about to ask a question?

00:07:21.320 --> 00:07:25.679
You might not notice that you're noticing, but you notice.

00:07:25.679 --> 00:07:30.619
And as soon as you start teaching online, a lot of that is taken away.

00:07:30.619 --> 00:07:38.119
If you take all of it away, you're going to find it very, very difficult to teach.

00:07:38.160 --> 00:07:46.600
What I suggest you do is get your students into some sort of webinar like this, but then

00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:51.760
have a few of them turn on their video so that you can see a few people.

00:07:51.760 --> 00:07:57.880
If, for example, you're using Zoom, which is my preferred video conferencing tool, take

00:07:57.880 --> 00:08:03.239
a half a dozen names at random and ask them to turn on video, and then focus your attention

00:08:03.239 --> 00:08:05.679
on those six.

00:08:05.679 --> 00:08:07.839
Ask them your questions.

00:08:07.839 --> 00:08:11.720
Pay attention to their faces just as you would in a real class.

00:08:11.720 --> 00:08:15.239
And in your next class, pick a different half dozen.

00:08:15.239 --> 00:08:18.239
This teaching practice predates video.

00:08:18.239 --> 00:08:19.239
It was quite common.

00:08:19.239 --> 00:08:20.880
It still is in some places.

00:08:20.880 --> 00:08:25.920
If you've got a large class, to pick a few people, bring them down front and focus your

00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:30.600
teaching on them for this hour, but then focus it on a different half dozen for the next

00:08:30.600 --> 00:08:32.400
hour and so on.

00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:33.960
They get individual attention.

00:08:33.960 --> 00:08:40.520
You get the kind of responsiveness you need to make improvisation and teaching lively.

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:44.840
And everybody else now has permission to turn off their video and reduce the load on the

00:08:44.840 --> 00:08:45.840
system.

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:50.760
If you're going to do this, please give people a way to opt out.

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:56.979
For a whole bunch of reasons, a lot of people are uncomfortable being on video online.

00:08:56.979 --> 00:09:01.159
If you've ever had to deal with harassment or a stalker, you don't want images of yourself

00:09:01.159 --> 00:09:03.479
appearing that might go out of your control.

00:09:03.479 --> 00:09:06.239
People have many other issues.

00:09:06.239 --> 00:09:10.080
If they're working at home for the first time, for example, maybe they don't want others

00:09:10.080 --> 00:09:15.000
to be able to see the mess in the background, the kids playing, and so on.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:20.719
So invite people, don't mandate it, but try to get, as I said, four, five, or six people

00:09:20.719 --> 00:09:23.239
that you're directing your teaching to.

00:09:23.239 --> 00:09:28.760
That will keep you engaged and you'll do a better job with the teaching.

00:09:28.760 --> 00:09:33.640
The next one was recommended by one of my colleagues, and I'm embarrassed that I didn't

00:09:33.640 --> 00:09:37.960
think of it because it reveals my expert blind spot.

00:09:37.960 --> 00:09:44.159
The first time you move your class online, give them a tour of the tool that you're using.

00:09:44.159 --> 00:09:48.119
They probably haven't seen Zoom or whatever you've got.

00:09:48.119 --> 00:09:51.960
They might not know where to click the button to mute.

00:09:51.960 --> 00:09:57.479
Seems obvious once you know, it's anything but if you've just been thrown into it.

00:09:57.479 --> 00:10:02.840
So taking 10 minutes at the start of your first online lecture to show people how you're

00:10:02.840 --> 00:10:09.960
expecting them to use the tool, or taking an hour beforehand to take a few screenshots

00:10:09.960 --> 00:10:14.799
and then share those with the class, can save a lot of grief.

00:10:14.799 --> 00:10:20.239
If you're going to do this, make sure that you're logged in as a normal user, not as

00:10:20.239 --> 00:10:25.479
the teacher or the conference organizer, when you're giving the tool.

00:10:25.479 --> 00:10:30.840
Because if you're logged in as a super user, you will see a different set of tools that

00:10:30.840 --> 00:10:36.200
they don't have, and that will confuse them.

00:10:36.200 --> 00:10:40.520
The next one up is to direct traffic.

00:10:40.520 --> 00:10:44.559
You don't have to go full North Korean, that's where this picture's from.

00:10:44.559 --> 00:10:49.520
But again, for a lot of people, this is their first time being in some sort of structured

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:51.960
formal setting online.

00:10:51.960 --> 00:10:55.359
So always give them verbal cues.

00:10:55.359 --> 00:10:58.400
Ask them to put their questions in the chat.

00:10:58.400 --> 00:11:04.640
Ask them to add their answers to a homework question to the shared Google Doc.

00:11:04.640 --> 00:11:10.000
Call on them by name when you want them to speak, or ask them to type something like

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:16.320
slash hand or raise hand in the chat when they want to speak.

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:23.559
Make sure that they're all getting direction about what they're supposed to do next.

00:11:23.559 --> 00:11:26.719
After a while, you can dial that down.

00:11:26.719 --> 00:11:29.719
But I have found in my own teaching that I don't.

00:11:29.719 --> 00:11:35.440
I constantly do it because I've constantly got people who are new or who are coming in

00:11:35.440 --> 00:11:41.479
from somebody else's class where they might have evolved a different set of conventions.

00:11:41.479 --> 00:11:46.239
Whatever it is, you as the tour guide telling people now we're moving on to the Renaissance

00:11:46.239 --> 00:11:52.559
Arts section, everybody step this way, again, it takes away a lot of the uncertainty.

00:11:52.559 --> 00:11:58.559
And right now, people have got enough uncertainty to deal with.

00:11:58.559 --> 00:12:03.400
One other point on this, mute early and mute often.

00:12:03.400 --> 00:12:09.479
By default now when I'm in Zoom, after somebody finishes speaking, I don't wait for them to

00:12:09.479 --> 00:12:10.479
mute.

00:12:10.479 --> 00:12:12.080
I don't even mute them.

00:12:12.080 --> 00:12:15.719
I instinctively now hit the mute all button.

00:12:15.719 --> 00:12:21.239
I put everybody back in a muted state, even if they don't need to be, because that way

00:12:21.239 --> 00:12:24.159
I never forget to.

00:12:24.159 --> 00:12:29.919
You can do a very good class audio only or audio with slides.

00:12:29.919 --> 00:12:33.440
Video is helpful, but it's not essential.

00:12:33.440 --> 00:12:37.919
And I can prove this by asking, what would happen if we left you with video of me talking

00:12:37.919 --> 00:12:41.239
right now but turned off the sound?

00:12:41.239 --> 00:12:43.640
You wouldn't learn anything.

00:12:43.640 --> 00:12:47.679
You've got to make sure that everybody can be heard.

00:12:47.679 --> 00:12:53.799
You've got to make sure that you're not drowned out by feedback, by background noise, or crucially

00:12:53.799 --> 00:12:58.080
by somebody who constantly wants to be the next one to ask the question and constantly

00:12:58.080 --> 00:13:02.320
wants to jump in first.

00:13:02.320 --> 00:13:09.119
One thing that I do to ensure that is I actually keep a written list of names beside me of

00:13:09.119 --> 00:13:13.119
the people that I'm focusing my teaching on, that half dozen I referred to earlier.

00:13:13.119 --> 00:13:17.599
Every time I interact with them, I just put a tick beside their name.

00:13:17.599 --> 00:13:24.239
So that I can very quickly see who I have been talking to and who I haven't been talking to.

00:13:24.239 --> 00:13:29.719
That way I can distribute my attention more or less fairly among those half dozen.

00:13:29.719 --> 00:13:35.520
And if somebody is constantly trying to jump in, I can say, no, it's not your turn.

00:13:35.520 --> 00:13:37.859
We're trying to take turns here.

00:13:37.859 --> 00:13:43.400
If you are relying on people to unmute themselves and just jump in with their questions, your

00:13:43.400 --> 00:13:46.919
class is going to be dominated by a couple of extroverts.

00:13:46.919 --> 00:13:51.440
And everybody else will very quickly learn to not even bother to try to ask questions

00:13:51.440 --> 00:13:55.919
or to contribute ideas because they can never get in fast enough.

00:13:55.919 --> 00:14:01.239
Mute early, mute often, and then have people request the microphone in order to speak so

00:14:01.239 --> 00:14:04.200
that you do the unmuting.

00:14:04.200 --> 00:14:06.880
And as I said, call on people by name.

00:14:06.880 --> 00:14:14.799
If I ask the room, are there any questions, it will be followed with silence.

00:14:14.799 --> 00:14:18.239
Sometimes that silence means nobody has any questions.

00:14:18.239 --> 00:14:22.440
Sometimes that silence means people have questions, but they don't want to look foolish.

00:14:22.440 --> 00:14:27.440
And sometimes that silence means they're very busy typing and the question is going to pop

00:14:27.440 --> 00:14:33.239
up in 15 seconds, by which point I will probably have moved on.

00:14:33.359 --> 00:14:39.840
Instead, when I want somebody to contribute, I call on them by name.

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:43.400
And if they want to pass, if they say, I don't have an answer, I don't feel like this is the

00:14:43.400 --> 00:14:47.559
right time, that's fine, I'll move on to the next person.

00:14:47.559 --> 00:14:53.719
Calling on people by name also helps you level out your classroom.

00:14:53.719 --> 00:15:00.000
You are about to discover that some of your learners think much more quickly than others.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.960
That doesn't mean they're smarter.

00:15:02.960 --> 00:15:05.080
Doesn't mean they're producing better work.

00:15:05.080 --> 00:15:10.119
It just means that their first response comes faster.

00:15:10.119 --> 00:15:15.599
If you are calling on people by name, you can even that out by throwing softballs to people

00:15:15.599 --> 00:15:19.520
who might need a little bit more time, throwing harder questions at people who are a little

00:15:19.520 --> 00:15:27.280
quicker, and that way the whole class is progressing at about the same rate.

00:15:27.280 --> 00:15:29.599
This is all a lot to manage.

00:15:29.640 --> 00:15:33.479
So this brings us to the other big takeaway.

00:15:33.479 --> 00:15:34.679
Don't teach alone.

00:15:34.679 --> 00:15:40.719
If you can possibly avoid it, don't be the only person trying to run things.

00:15:40.719 --> 00:15:44.520
Every great surgeon has a great nurse beside her.

00:15:44.520 --> 00:15:47.000
Every great teacher has a co-teacher.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:53.479
It could be a fellow instructor, it could be a TA, it could be one of your learners that

00:15:53.479 --> 00:15:59.479
you've approached to say, you seem to be okay with this material, can I ask you a favor?

00:15:59.559 --> 00:16:05.760
Whoever it is, you want somebody else keeping track of whose turn it is to speak next, somebody

00:16:05.760 --> 00:16:11.719
else making sure that the slides are presenting properly, somebody else who is wrangling that

00:16:11.719 --> 00:16:15.479
shared document that we're going to talk about in a couple of minutes.

00:16:15.479 --> 00:16:21.280
You want a co-pilot who's worrying about everything that isn't the actual delivery of the lesson

00:16:21.280 --> 00:16:26.640
in the moment to free you up to focus on your slides and what you're saying.

00:16:26.719 --> 00:16:31.239
I've got that right now, and it makes a world of difference.

00:16:31.239 --> 00:16:39.520
It doesn't take a lot of practice to learn how to do that, and it does also mean that

00:16:39.520 --> 00:16:46.599
if next week you're unable to make a scheduled class for whatever reason, there's somebody

00:16:46.599 --> 00:16:52.440
else who's at least partly familiar with what you're teaching and with how you're delivering it.

00:16:53.440 --> 00:16:59.239
So, do a dry run.

00:16:59.239 --> 00:17:05.079
I have a list someplace of things that have gone wrong while I've been teaching.

00:17:05.079 --> 00:17:07.839
I've fallen off stage twice and concussed myself once.

00:17:07.839 --> 00:17:13.280
I've had a fistfight break out, I've had a projector catch fire, I've had a woman go

00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:21.280
into labor, and I once actually fell asleep in one of my own lectures.

00:17:21.319 --> 00:17:22.439
Those are the easy ones.

00:17:22.439 --> 00:17:27.680
The hard one is nobody told me there was a firewall, so all of a sudden I can't get at

00:17:27.680 --> 00:17:29.880
any of the data sets.

00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:34.920
Nobody told me that they've updated Zoom and some of the controls have moved or behave

00:17:34.920 --> 00:17:41.319
differently, or I know all of that, but I've never done it with Robert, I've never done

00:17:41.319 --> 00:17:47.439
it with Karina, and so we're used to using the tool in different ways.

00:17:47.439 --> 00:17:52.560
Getting 10 or 15 minutes, half an hour before you're supposed to start talking, can make

00:17:52.560 --> 00:18:01.640
a world of difference to delivery and it can lower your blood pressure considerably.

00:18:01.640 --> 00:18:08.880
Another small note, keep your notes beside you.

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:13.640
I've got a laptop on my desk and then I've got a large screen monitor above it.

00:18:13.640 --> 00:18:16.880
I think that's a fairly common setup these days.

00:18:16.880 --> 00:18:22.280
What that meant was that going back a while, whenever I was teaching, I was looking up

00:18:22.280 --> 00:18:26.920
and had my head tilted back, and my daughter eventually told me that as far as she was

00:18:26.920 --> 00:18:33.000
concerned, my webcam was a nose cam, and that's why I don't have a picture for this slide.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:37.280
If you've got your notes beside you, it's very natural to turn your head to the side,

00:18:37.280 --> 00:18:40.920
check what you're going to say next, and come back to your lecture.

00:18:40.920 --> 00:18:46.239
If you've got the slides up here, it's not something you're used to doing, and the angle

00:18:46.280 --> 00:18:47.520
can be rather unflattering.

00:18:47.520 --> 00:18:53.520
I know it's a small thing, but the small things add up.

00:18:53.520 --> 00:19:00.119
A much larger thing, please add speaker's notes to your slides.

00:19:00.119 --> 00:19:05.520
You are about to discover that a lot of your learners have trouble seeing or hearing.

00:19:05.520 --> 00:19:10.040
They've got good compensating strategies or accommodation strategies in a live classroom

00:19:10.040 --> 00:19:14.280
because they've got a lifetime of experience doing this.

00:19:14.319 --> 00:19:21.239
They may not have the same support now that you're bailing everything online.

00:19:21.239 --> 00:19:27.560
If you put speaker's notes in your slides, it makes the slides more findable because

00:19:27.560 --> 00:19:29.760
search tools know how to index them.

00:19:29.760 --> 00:19:34.760
It makes the slides more usable because people can understand after the fact what you meant

00:19:34.760 --> 00:19:41.640
by that picture, but crucially, it makes them more accessible, and however hard you think

00:19:41.959 --> 00:19:48.479
life is suddenly being thrown online, it's a lot harder if you're partially sighted or

00:19:48.479 --> 00:19:50.400
fully deaf.

00:19:50.400 --> 00:19:56.839
Please don't make life harder for people who already have more to struggle with.

00:19:56.839 --> 00:20:00.319
In fact, using accessibility tools helps everyone.

00:20:00.319 --> 00:20:06.719
I don't know if you can see my cursor right now, but I've used the accessibility tools

00:20:06.839 --> 00:20:13.599
on the Mac to make it as large as possible so that it's easier for people to see on video.

00:20:13.599 --> 00:20:16.040
I do that whenever I'm teaching.

00:20:16.040 --> 00:20:22.599
I use an enlarged cursor because a small cursor in a small window is really, really hard to see.

00:20:22.599 --> 00:20:28.959
I switch to high contrast mode so that people who might be sizing down the screen or might

00:20:28.959 --> 00:20:33.560
be on older devices or might just have crappy monitors have a better chance of being able

00:20:33.599 --> 00:20:36.640
to see what's going on.

00:20:36.640 --> 00:20:38.800
All of these tools help.

00:20:38.800 --> 00:20:44.959
Keycasting tools that will show people on screen all of the control keys, option keys,

00:20:44.959 --> 00:20:47.560
and other things that you're typing.

00:20:47.560 --> 00:20:53.400
You should be using those anyway when you're teaching so that somebody doesn't think you're

00:20:53.400 --> 00:20:54.959
typing 100 characters a second.

00:20:54.959 --> 00:20:58.680
They realize that you hit tab and got file name completion.

00:20:58.680 --> 00:21:00.439
Keycaster is one that you can use.

00:21:00.439 --> 00:21:01.839
Mouse Pose is another.

00:21:01.839 --> 00:21:04.680
There's a lot of accessibility tools out there.

00:21:04.680 --> 00:21:08.000
Most of them are either free or very cheap.

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:12.719
Most of them are fairly easy to set up, and they will all help with your online teaching.

00:21:12.719 --> 00:21:17.079
And when you're done, keep using them when you go back in the classroom because they'll make life

00:21:17.079 --> 00:21:20.280
better for everyone.

00:21:20.280 --> 00:21:23.599
This recommendation comes again from Elizabeth Wicks.

00:21:23.599 --> 00:21:27.400
Teach from your smallest screen.

00:21:27.439 --> 00:21:35.040
If I try to take my half meter wide monitor and squeeze it down into a little video window,

00:21:35.040 --> 00:21:38.959
the video quality is going to be pretty grainy and the bandwidth demands are going to be

00:21:38.959 --> 00:21:40.920
pretty heavy.

00:21:40.920 --> 00:21:46.680
I'm not suggesting that you teach from a tiny handheld device like this, but please remember

00:21:46.680 --> 00:21:52.560
that most of your learners will be using smaller and older gear than you've got.

00:21:52.560 --> 00:21:57.119
You want to be at the bottom of the pack when you're the one sending out the video

00:21:57.160 --> 00:22:00.599
because that has the greatest chance of working everywhere.

00:22:00.599 --> 00:22:03.439
And I'll add a personal footnote to this.

00:22:03.439 --> 00:22:11.160
It's difficult to teach with an IDE when you're screen sharing because once you've sized things

00:22:11.160 --> 00:22:17.000
down, all of the controls in the IDE for different tabs, different menus, and so forth,

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:22.800
all of those things that are really helpful, they're taking up a lot of space and you don't

00:22:22.920 --> 00:22:27.599
have a lot of leftover real estate for your own typing.

00:22:27.599 --> 00:22:33.079
I have seen people put RStudio IDE into a mode where only one pane is being shown at

00:22:33.079 --> 00:22:35.560
a time.

00:22:35.560 --> 00:22:39.800
That's great from a real estate point of view, but now it looks very different from what

00:22:39.800 --> 00:22:40.800
people are used to.

00:22:40.800 --> 00:22:43.239
I don't have a solution for this one.

00:22:43.239 --> 00:22:47.560
Ask your learners what they prefer.

00:22:47.599 --> 00:22:53.680
Going back to a topic from a few minutes ago, your voice matters more than your face.

00:22:53.680 --> 00:22:57.959
You can switch off video or you can go to still images like this one and give a decent

00:22:57.959 --> 00:22:58.959
class.

00:22:58.959 --> 00:23:04.800
You cannot lose voice or voice quality and still have a decent class.

00:23:04.800 --> 00:23:12.479
My setup is a Samsung microphone and a $25 stand from my local music store.

00:23:12.479 --> 00:23:17.920
I got the stand so that the microphone would be far enough away from the keyboard that

00:23:17.920 --> 00:23:21.640
it wouldn't be filled with all the clicking as I type.

00:23:21.640 --> 00:23:26.599
You can still hear the clicking, but it's a soft background noise rather than thunder.

00:23:26.599 --> 00:23:32.479
Again, try out your rig with your co-instructor or with some randomly selected student, or

00:23:32.479 --> 00:23:36.479
if you don't have anybody else, mail me and I will listen to it.

00:23:37.079 --> 00:23:44.280
But getting the mic up level with your head, about 30 centimeters away from your mouth

00:23:44.280 --> 00:23:48.719
and away from your keyboard, and that's as much as you need to do now.

00:23:48.719 --> 00:23:53.439
If later on you want to go get spit guards and swaffles and do the full rig, absolutely,

00:23:53.439 --> 00:23:58.439
knock yourself out, but you don't need to do that first week.

00:23:58.439 --> 00:24:05.599
What you do need to do is turn off your notifications.

00:24:05.599 --> 00:24:11.920
You don't want things popping up on screen constantly telling you that you've got mail,

00:24:11.920 --> 00:24:15.800
that you've got something on Twitter you should be looking at.

00:24:15.800 --> 00:24:21.719
I turn Slack off completely whenever I'm teaching unless I'm using it to communicate with my

00:24:21.719 --> 00:24:26.959
students because it's just a distraction.

00:24:26.959 --> 00:24:30.439
You can ask them to turn theirs off as well.

00:24:30.439 --> 00:24:33.280
I know that most won't.

00:24:33.280 --> 00:24:39.079
And if you go into an in-person classroom, stand at the back and look over people's shoulders,

00:24:39.079 --> 00:24:42.760
at any given time about a third of them are doing something on their laptop.

00:24:42.760 --> 00:24:46.040
Some of it is course related, some of it isn't.

00:24:46.040 --> 00:24:51.560
Once they're in an online environment, there's going to be more of that, but it's worth asking.

00:24:51.560 --> 00:24:55.920
Again, if you've got a focus group of about half a dozen that you're directing most of

00:24:55.920 --> 00:25:03.280
your teaching to, they're more likely to switch off distractions and actually be engaged

00:25:03.280 --> 00:25:06.800
because they're being called on with higher frequency.

00:25:06.800 --> 00:25:12.959
So you can get a high quality experience for a small group and everybody else is going

00:25:12.959 --> 00:25:17.000
to do what they would do anyway.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:20.680
Now we come to that shared doc that I've been talking about.

00:25:20.680 --> 00:25:27.680
Excuse me a second, I need a mouthful of tea.

00:25:27.680 --> 00:25:33.719
Every time I teach online, I create something like a Google Doc or a HackMD, for those of

00:25:33.719 --> 00:25:40.599
you who love Markdown, and I give edit permission to the people I'm teaching.

00:25:40.599 --> 00:25:45.640
Whenever I ask a question and want a response from everybody, I now have options.

00:25:45.640 --> 00:25:51.520
I can either tell them, put it in the chat, which I will do if I'm looking for a one word

00:25:51.520 --> 00:25:57.439
or two word response, or if I'm asking something a little larger and they need to show me a

00:25:57.439 --> 00:26:04.680
bit of code, write a couple of sentences, something like that, they paste it into the document.

00:26:04.680 --> 00:26:12.400
I say paste it in because a lot of people don't want you to see them typing.

00:26:12.439 --> 00:26:15.880
I'm comfortable with that, but I've been doing this for years.

00:26:15.880 --> 00:26:21.079
What I see a lot of newcomers do is have a separate text editor where they're composing

00:26:21.079 --> 00:26:24.719
their answer to question number three, and then they'll copy it and they'll just paste

00:26:24.719 --> 00:26:26.959
it into the Google Doc.

00:26:26.959 --> 00:26:28.520
That's cool.

00:26:28.520 --> 00:26:33.319
As they become more comfortable, maybe they'll do their editing directly in the doc so that

00:26:33.319 --> 00:26:36.319
others can see their mistakes and see them being corrected.

00:26:36.319 --> 00:26:38.119
That's cool too.

00:26:38.119 --> 00:26:42.520
The important thing is that it allows you to see their work in real time, and it allows

00:26:42.520 --> 00:26:45.680
them to see one another's work in real time.

00:26:45.680 --> 00:26:50.640
That dramatically improves engagement, and you get a lot of peer to peer learning.

00:26:50.640 --> 00:26:57.560
If you ask people to, for example, find the height of the tallest person in Louisiana

00:26:57.560 --> 00:27:04.959
in 1920 using a dplyr pipeline, there are three or four plausible ways to arrange the

00:27:04.959 --> 00:27:07.199
commands to do that.

00:27:07.280 --> 00:27:11.640
Each person will have one, and then they'll be able to glance at a few others in the document

00:27:11.640 --> 00:27:13.680
and go, oh, that's cool.

00:27:13.680 --> 00:27:20.400
It's exactly like what we do in a music class where I say, okay, Janet, you play this piece.

00:27:20.400 --> 00:27:23.959
Okay, now, Janine, you play this piece.

00:27:23.959 --> 00:27:27.800
We're used to seeing and hearing others work in live contexts.

00:27:27.800 --> 00:27:35.800
We can do that online, and this is probably the biggest change in my teaching practice

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:41.479
over the last 10 years is trusting learners to share work with each other in real time.

00:27:41.479 --> 00:27:44.319
A couple of caveats for this.

00:27:44.319 --> 00:27:49.520
Number one, if you're going to do it, keep that list of half a dozen names or the entire

00:27:49.520 --> 00:27:55.640
class name, depending on how many are contributing to the doc, paste it into the doc before they

00:27:55.640 --> 00:28:01.000
start typing, and do that for each question so that everybody knows where they're supposed

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:03.119
to start typing.

00:28:03.119 --> 00:28:08.160
If you say, just add this to the doc, you'll have two dozen people putting their cursors

00:28:08.160 --> 00:28:12.719
on top of each other and colliding with one another's work.

00:28:12.719 --> 00:28:14.319
That's not helpful.

00:28:14.319 --> 00:28:17.359
They'll very quickly opt out because it's frustrating.

00:28:17.359 --> 00:28:21.979
If on the other hand, I've got a list of names with a couple of blank lines between them

00:28:21.979 --> 00:28:26.400
in a text file, and I paste it into the doc, everybody immediately knows where to type

00:28:26.400 --> 00:28:29.719
and there's no collisions.

00:28:29.719 --> 00:28:32.719
The second thing has to do with scope.

00:28:32.719 --> 00:28:38.640
Google Doc will comfortably support 14 or 15, maybe 16 concurrent typists.

00:28:38.640 --> 00:28:40.459
It won't support 30.

00:28:40.459 --> 00:28:44.920
You'll see a sudden dramatic slowdown at some threshold, and I've never done the experiments

00:28:44.920 --> 00:28:49.560
to measure where it is, but it's somewhere between a dozen and 20.

00:28:49.560 --> 00:28:56.119
Again, you solve this problem by having a subset of people contributing to the shared

00:28:56.119 --> 00:29:01.400
document and swapping that up each time you take a coffee break, each time you restart

00:29:01.400 --> 00:29:04.400
your class.

00:29:04.400 --> 00:29:08.959
Talked about this before, keep track of who has and hasn't spoken to make sure that the

00:29:08.959 --> 00:29:12.199
people who aren't extroverts are getting airtime.

00:29:12.199 --> 00:29:18.640
It doesn't have to be electronic, just a piece of paper and a pencil beside you, putting

00:29:18.640 --> 00:29:24.020
tick marks in, trying to make sure that you distribute your attention fairly so that everybody

00:29:24.020 --> 00:29:31.140
feels like they're not just allowed in the room, but they're welcome in the room.

00:29:31.140 --> 00:29:37.819
Ask fill call is a pretty common tactic from the days of broadcast radio.

00:29:37.819 --> 00:29:46.140
If I ask a question, it's going to take people a while to formulate an answer.

00:29:46.140 --> 00:29:51.900
If I'm asking them for a long answer, three lines of code, for example, it's probably

00:29:51.900 --> 00:30:02.579
going to take them 15 seconds and even a gap of seven seconds, which you just

00:30:02.579 --> 00:30:06.699
heard can be really uncomfortable.

00:30:06.699 --> 00:30:12.060
If I want somebody to come in with a question, I ask the question, and then as they're composing

00:30:12.060 --> 00:30:16.060
their answer, I fill the air.

00:30:16.060 --> 00:30:21.660
I say something else, I elaborate on a previous point, they'll probably tune me out while

00:30:21.660 --> 00:30:27.900
they focus on their answer, so it can't be anything too important, but it's like making

00:30:27.900 --> 00:30:32.520
small talk while somebody is setting the table.

00:30:32.520 --> 00:30:36.500
You want to ask your question, you want to fill in a little bit so that there's not dead

00:30:36.500 --> 00:30:42.339
air, and then you want to say, okay, Sarah, now what have you got for us?

00:30:42.339 --> 00:30:47.060
Again, you're doing this to make up for the lack of social cues.

00:30:47.060 --> 00:30:51.339
You don't have that peripheral awareness of people's attention, so you're going to have

00:30:51.339 --> 00:30:56.699
to be more directive.

00:30:56.699 --> 00:31:02.979
Another way that you can take advantage of the online teaching is to ask people for predictions.

00:31:02.979 --> 00:31:06.140
This is particularly important when you're teaching coding.

00:31:06.140 --> 00:31:11.859
If I'm teaching a programming class, I'm probably sharing my screen so that you can see the

00:31:11.859 --> 00:31:14.699
code as I'm building it.

00:31:14.699 --> 00:31:19.579
Every time I'm about to do something, I have an opportunity to say, all right, everybody,

00:31:19.579 --> 00:31:23.140
in the chat, what's going to happen if I run it now?

00:31:23.140 --> 00:31:27.619
I've just added this line, how's it going to behave?

00:31:27.619 --> 00:31:33.260
Pedagogically, this is forcing people to pull recent knowledge back into consciousness and

00:31:33.260 --> 00:31:35.900
use it and reinforce it.

00:31:35.900 --> 00:31:38.540
That will help them learn and remember.

00:31:38.540 --> 00:31:41.900
From a motivational point of view, it increases their engagement.

00:31:41.900 --> 00:31:47.319
They're constantly being asked to think and to contribute, and from your point of view,

00:31:47.319 --> 00:31:51.079
it gives you a very quick formative assessment.

00:31:51.079 --> 00:31:56.319
For those who don't know the term, formative assessment is what you do during learning

00:31:56.319 --> 00:31:59.800
to find out whether or not people are learning.

00:31:59.800 --> 00:32:02.400
It's your real-time feedback loop.

00:32:02.400 --> 00:32:07.479
You cannot trust people to go, uh-huh, I got it, I got it, because a lot of people will

00:32:07.479 --> 00:32:08.479
lie.

00:32:08.479 --> 00:32:11.640
They'll say they have it when they don't, or they'll believe that they do, but they'll

00:32:11.640 --> 00:32:12.640
be wrong.

00:32:12.959 --> 00:32:18.880
And they're even more likely to mislead this way when you're teaching online.

00:32:18.880 --> 00:32:24.900
If on the other hand, I say, all right, Paul and Ahmed, what's this going to do next?

00:32:24.900 --> 00:32:29.040
If they're right, you know that they're understanding.

00:32:29.040 --> 00:32:34.000
If they're wrong, then you know that you've got something to explain, to clarify, or to

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:38.719
cover a second time, and you can do it right then and there before their misconception

00:32:38.800 --> 00:32:45.599
has a chance to set in concrete.

00:32:45.599 --> 00:32:50.239
This is a point where I would normally poll my class to say how many of you know breakout

00:32:50.239 --> 00:32:51.839
rooms.

00:32:51.839 --> 00:32:58.800
For those of you who don't, if you're using something like Zoom, you can go down and put

00:32:58.800 --> 00:33:01.819
everybody into a small sub-conversation.

00:33:01.819 --> 00:33:05.760
You can assign them manually, or you can assign them at random.

00:33:05.800 --> 00:33:10.319
You can vary the size of the rooms, and you can determine how long they're in that side

00:33:10.319 --> 00:33:13.000
conversation.

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:14.000
Here's a question.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:16.439
The answer isn't obvious.

00:33:16.439 --> 00:33:21.079
Everybody go and think about it, and then argue with your three partners, and see if

00:33:21.079 --> 00:33:25.599
you can come to a consensus about what this code does or doesn't do.

00:33:25.599 --> 00:33:28.160
Three, two, one, go.

00:33:28.160 --> 00:33:35.319
You've got a couple of minutes, and then I pull you back, and I poll a couple of people.

00:33:35.319 --> 00:33:41.859
This emulates a practice called peer instruction, which is the most effective scalable teaching

00:33:41.859 --> 00:33:44.319
practice we know.

00:33:44.319 --> 00:33:50.000
The slide deck has a link to a video from a math class in India in 2013 that illustrates

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:51.719
the method.

00:33:51.719 --> 00:33:58.199
Short version is, I ask a motivating question, something whose answer requires more than

00:33:58.199 --> 00:34:01.339
just factual recall.

00:34:01.339 --> 00:34:06.339
You all then go and argue with each other over the answer, and then I pull you back

00:34:06.339 --> 00:34:08.459
and give you the explanation.

00:34:08.459 --> 00:34:10.100
Why the argument stage?

00:34:10.100 --> 00:34:14.820
Because that's when you have to think through the inconsistencies or gaps in your mental

00:34:14.820 --> 00:34:18.739
model, and you've got other people there who can fill them in.

00:34:18.739 --> 00:34:23.020
One of the great discoveries is, it doesn't really matter if anybody in one of these little

00:34:23.020 --> 00:34:24.939
discussion groups is right at the start.

00:34:24.939 --> 00:34:29.340
What matters is that you disagree, so that you can clear up each other's misconceptions.

00:34:29.939 --> 00:34:32.699
Pedagogically, it's a well-justified method.

00:34:32.699 --> 00:34:37.580
Practically, it also helps with motivation, because instead of only teaching to half a

00:34:37.580 --> 00:34:44.379
dozen for half an hour, you can teach to that half dozen, and then say, okay, now everybody's

00:34:44.379 --> 00:34:49.780
going into a small discussion group, and then I'm bringing you back, and now they have to

00:34:49.780 --> 00:34:52.020
interact with their peers.

00:34:52.020 --> 00:34:56.739
Again, you want people to be able to opt out.

00:34:56.739 --> 00:35:00.260
They may not be in a situation where they can have a conversation.

00:35:00.260 --> 00:35:05.419
They might be in the living room, muted, because the entire family is here at the moment.

00:35:05.419 --> 00:35:06.500
You've got to respect that.

00:35:06.500 --> 00:35:11.179
Some people may be uncomfortable arguing with strangers at the outset of a class.

00:35:11.179 --> 00:35:12.179
You respect that.

00:35:12.179 --> 00:35:17.020
But for everyone else, it's a very effective technique.

00:35:17.020 --> 00:35:24.659
One of the things that we can't do with any video tool I have today is put people into

00:35:24.659 --> 00:35:29.300
breakout rooms in which they can all screen share with each other.

00:35:29.300 --> 00:35:34.899
I would really like to be able to put people into pairs and have them screen share so that

00:35:34.899 --> 00:35:37.459
they can co-program.

00:35:37.459 --> 00:35:42.500
The technology will get there eventually, but something like that or a shared whiteboard

00:35:42.500 --> 00:35:46.379
in the breakout room would probably help a lot.

00:35:46.379 --> 00:35:48.179
We just have to wait.

00:35:48.179 --> 00:35:53.679
And since I mentioned whiteboards, Zoom provides polls so that you can ask people questions

00:35:53.679 --> 00:35:56.500
in real time and do a survey.

00:35:56.500 --> 00:35:59.000
It also provides a whiteboard.

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:01.199
Don't try to use it yet.

00:36:01.199 --> 00:36:05.199
Become comfortable with the online teaching, sort out some of your other problems, and

00:36:05.199 --> 00:36:09.479
then start to try to take advantage of all the science fiction you've been handed.

00:36:09.479 --> 00:36:11.360
You don't need it today.

00:36:11.360 --> 00:36:17.479
Take advantage of it tomorrow.

00:36:17.479 --> 00:36:22.739
The quote here comes from my wife, who once explained to me that the basic unit of teaching

00:36:22.739 --> 00:36:24.580
is the bladder.

00:36:24.580 --> 00:36:26.659
And I said, I've never thought of it that way.

00:36:26.659 --> 00:36:29.659
And she said, you've never been pregnant.

00:36:29.659 --> 00:36:32.300
You need to take a break every hour.

00:36:32.300 --> 00:36:33.860
Your back's going to get sore.

00:36:33.860 --> 00:36:35.860
Your voice is going to get hoarse.

00:36:35.860 --> 00:36:40.419
Your learners are probably in situations that are no more comfortable than yours and quite

00:36:40.419 --> 00:36:42.179
probably less.

00:36:42.179 --> 00:36:47.500
And even when they're comfortable, it's a long day and it's a lot of coffee.

00:36:47.500 --> 00:36:50.340
Make sure that you set yourself a timer.

00:36:50.340 --> 00:36:55.979
I do it on my phone and have it go off at 45 minutes.

00:36:55.979 --> 00:37:01.500
I found that when I was setting timers for an hour, because I always drift a little over,

00:37:01.500 --> 00:37:05.580
we were only taking breaks about every 75 or 80 minutes.

00:37:05.580 --> 00:37:11.260
If I set the timer for 45 minutes, I'm pretty much guaranteed a break every hour.

00:37:11.260 --> 00:37:17.219
Whatever I set it for, I always go over 5 or 10 minutes.

00:37:17.219 --> 00:37:24.300
And to wrap up before we start taking questions, I want you all to know that nobody knows anything

00:37:24.300 --> 00:37:27.100
right now.

00:37:27.100 --> 00:37:34.340
We've been teaching online in relatively small numbers in relatively constrained technological

00:37:34.340 --> 00:37:41.139
environments for a couple of decades, maybe three.

00:37:41.139 --> 00:37:43.860
And on the one hand, that sounds like a lot.

00:37:43.860 --> 00:37:50.500
But on the other, we are about to invent more different ways to teach online in the

00:37:50.500 --> 00:37:59.139
next 12 months than we know in total today, because we're about to do a whole lot of experiments.

00:37:59.139 --> 00:38:02.379
You're going to suck at this at first, but that's a necessary first step towards being

00:38:02.379 --> 00:38:04.340
good at it.

00:38:04.340 --> 00:38:07.139
Don't beat yourself up.

00:38:07.139 --> 00:38:09.780
And don't be afraid to experiment.

00:38:09.780 --> 00:38:15.020
Don't be afraid to try things and then to say, all right, that didn't work.

00:38:15.020 --> 00:38:19.500
I think everybody understands that these are unusual circumstances.

00:38:19.500 --> 00:38:26.500
I think everybody, I hope, is going to give people a little bit of slack, give them a

00:38:26.500 --> 00:38:32.179
little bit of allowance because of the unusual circumstances.

00:38:32.179 --> 00:38:37.899
So there's never been a better time to try new things.

00:38:37.899 --> 00:38:41.300
Your audience will never be more understanding.

00:38:41.300 --> 00:38:43.860
And as I said at the outset, we're here to help.

00:38:43.860 --> 00:38:51.540
If there's anything we can do, if there's any questions you have, throw them at us.

00:38:51.540 --> 00:38:58.260
Last thing before we dive into the close, if you've got time to do any reading, I highly

00:38:58.260 --> 00:39:02.659
recommend this book by Brookfield and Preskill.

00:39:02.659 --> 00:39:10.540
I've been talking about things with people in large groups since I was about 16.

00:39:10.540 --> 00:39:16.860
Of the 50 different techniques they catalog in this book, for having a productive discussion,

00:39:16.860 --> 00:39:22.939
I had only ever seen 15, and I've only ever seen five or six implemented online.

00:39:22.939 --> 00:39:28.979
This is a catalog of ways to get people to talk to one another and share information

00:39:28.979 --> 00:39:31.219
and make decisions.

00:39:31.219 --> 00:39:34.739
A lot of them are directly applicable to teaching.

00:39:34.739 --> 00:39:40.620
And even if you don't have direct customized technical support, they're all social conventions

00:39:40.620 --> 00:39:45.139
that are fairly easy to adopt in an online environment.

00:39:45.139 --> 00:39:50.340
Just to pick one example, suppose I've got half a dozen people that I'm focusing on.

00:39:50.340 --> 00:39:54.820
All right, I want all of you to put your answers to this question into the Google Doc.

00:39:54.820 --> 00:40:00.020
Okay, now that we've got those, I want you each to shift down one spot, bottom person

00:40:00.020 --> 00:40:06.219
comes to the top, and comment on the answer from the person that you're now looking at.

00:40:06.219 --> 00:40:08.939
Okay, now shift down one more.

00:40:08.939 --> 00:40:14.100
So now you're looking at an answer and a previous set of comments.

00:40:14.100 --> 00:40:18.739
People will learn so much from each other, and the peer-to-peer knowledge transfer will

00:40:18.739 --> 00:40:23.219
make up for so much of what you're losing by not having them physically present.

00:40:23.219 --> 00:40:28.540
And that's just one idea in a book full of 50.

00:40:28.540 --> 00:40:33.260
So here are some links that I found useful preparing this.

00:40:33.260 --> 00:40:38.459
Jason Bell in Australia, who I believe is here with us today, has a good video on what

00:40:38.459 --> 00:40:41.939
it's like to teach software carpentry workshops remotely.

00:40:41.939 --> 00:40:42.939
He's in Queensland.

00:40:42.939 --> 00:40:44.699
A lot of his learners are scattered.

00:40:44.699 --> 00:40:50.139
So he's had to figure out over the years how you teach programming when you are hundreds

00:40:50.139 --> 00:40:54.340
of kilometers away from all of your learners, and they're hundreds of kilometers away from

00:40:54.340 --> 00:40:55.340
each other.

00:40:55.939 --> 00:41:01.020
Elizabeth Wicks, I've cited a couple of times, has a really good set of tips for teaching

00:41:01.020 --> 00:41:04.780
tech subjects online.

00:41:04.780 --> 00:41:08.459
There's a growing number of comments in the RStudio community teaching discussion.

00:41:08.459 --> 00:41:11.139
You're all welcome to join in there.

00:41:11.139 --> 00:41:16.459
I'm a big fan of the piece that Laura Cernovich wrote in South Africa, what they learned from

00:41:16.459 --> 00:41:20.540
going online in Cape Town on short notice.

00:41:20.540 --> 00:41:27.979
That link there includes a sublink to a document about how to accommodate wildly different

00:41:27.979 --> 00:41:30.540
technical levels among your students.

00:41:30.540 --> 00:41:35.620
They'll have differential access to devices, to bandwidth, a whole bunch of things.

00:41:35.620 --> 00:41:38.979
They've got a lot of experience about how you accommodate that.

00:41:38.979 --> 00:41:40.840
So please follow that one up.

00:41:40.840 --> 00:41:44.219
And finally, just today, there was another blog post from the Carpentries.

00:41:44.219 --> 00:41:46.639
They're collecting their tips for teaching online.

00:41:46.639 --> 00:41:50.100
And again, there are links out to other resources.

00:41:50.100 --> 00:41:55.979
So with all of that done, I am hoping that some people will have questions.

00:41:55.979 --> 00:42:01.780
So Leon Jessen is saying that calling people by name is referred to as harpooning and discourage.

00:42:01.780 --> 00:42:02.780
Yes.

00:42:02.780 --> 00:42:06.060
Like any teaching technique, it can be used badly.

00:42:06.060 --> 00:42:09.340
You risk lower tier and introvert students leaving the teaching platform because they

00:42:09.340 --> 00:42:11.899
don't want to be called out.

00:42:11.899 --> 00:42:14.260
I respect that.

00:42:14.300 --> 00:42:20.100
And hopefully you can detect that or you can ask them in advance to message you if they

00:42:20.100 --> 00:42:24.179
are uncomfortable being called on.

00:42:24.179 --> 00:42:27.100
Just have them tell you, right?

00:42:27.100 --> 00:42:29.540
And respect whatever it is they do.

00:42:29.540 --> 00:42:32.540
Alyssa Dillman is looking for a list of accessibility tools.

00:42:32.540 --> 00:42:33.540
Yes.

00:42:33.540 --> 00:42:38.219
We've got a blog post hopefully up sometime next week.

00:42:38.219 --> 00:42:42.419
Does a cardioid mic help reduce the keyboard noise?

00:42:42.580 --> 00:42:44.379
It can.

00:42:44.379 --> 00:42:45.699
This Samson isn't a cardioid.

00:42:45.699 --> 00:42:47.620
I've just got it by trial and error.

00:42:47.620 --> 00:42:51.899
I've got it tilted at an angle where it seems to just pick up my voice and not the keyboard.

00:42:51.899 --> 00:42:56.139
For those who don't know the term, a cardioid mic picks up sound on one side or the other

00:42:56.139 --> 00:42:57.139
but not in between.

00:42:57.139 --> 00:42:58.139
Right?

00:42:58.139 --> 00:43:03.179
It's a directional microphone intended primarily for interviews where you've got two people

00:43:03.179 --> 00:43:05.419
on opposite sides of a mic.

00:43:05.419 --> 00:43:09.100
One of the reasons I got the Samson is that it's a cheap enough microphone that if I lose

00:43:09.100 --> 00:43:10.979
it while traveling, I'm not heartbroken.

00:43:11.379 --> 00:43:14.219
A good cardioid mic is going to be more expensive.

00:43:17.219 --> 00:43:21.580
Laura Asyon, feel lost reading all the feedback from the students in a shared doc?

00:43:21.580 --> 00:43:24.139
Do you have any tips to read the feedback?

00:43:24.139 --> 00:43:27.340
This is part of what your co-instructor can do for you.

00:43:27.340 --> 00:43:28.340
Right?

00:43:28.340 --> 00:43:34.179
Normally, when I'm teaching, I will call out one or two, but I've got somebody else there

00:43:34.179 --> 00:43:40.300
just as I've had Robert and Curtis going through your questions and flagging them, right?

00:43:40.620 --> 00:43:45.620
So that by the time I get there, somebody else has already done the first pass of filtering.

00:43:47.620 --> 00:43:51.820
Rhian Davis, for a smaller class doing quick intros at the start, absolutely, if you've

00:43:51.820 --> 00:43:55.540
got the time, if they're comfortable doing it.

00:43:55.540 --> 00:44:01.219
And then Kelsey Carrier, do you have a tactic for keeping track of participant responses

00:44:01.219 --> 00:44:04.620
when they may have strange or unrecognizable names?

00:44:04.620 --> 00:44:05.620
Yes.

00:44:05.939 --> 00:44:14.699
I sometimes now have learners whose name field is an emoji.

00:44:14.699 --> 00:44:19.500
In those cases, I will ask people, can you please change it for the duration of the session

00:44:19.500 --> 00:44:22.260
or just let me know how to address you?

00:44:22.260 --> 00:44:27.379
I find that asking people how do you want to be addressed also helps with internationalization

00:44:27.379 --> 00:44:30.379
of names and pronouns.

00:44:30.419 --> 00:44:36.379
I'm quite often not sure which of the several parts of someone's name they're most used

00:44:36.379 --> 00:44:40.300
to being called by, particularly when I get into East Asian and South Asian cultures that

00:44:40.300 --> 00:44:42.260
I'm not familiar with.

00:44:42.260 --> 00:44:49.820
And it's always a good idea to ask people what pronoun they would like you to use.

00:44:49.820 --> 00:44:53.300
Students don't turn on their video because they don't feel comfortable.

00:44:53.300 --> 00:44:55.540
This one's coming from Gabby Sandoval.

00:44:55.540 --> 00:45:00.459
In many cases, they don't turn it on because they're busy with other things.

00:45:00.459 --> 00:45:04.340
They don't want you to see that they are also doing their calculus homework while they're

00:45:04.340 --> 00:45:06.580
supposed to be in your class.

00:45:06.580 --> 00:45:07.580
I ask them.

00:45:07.580 --> 00:45:11.540
I try to create an environment in which they're comfortable being seen.

00:45:11.540 --> 00:45:15.300
Focusing on a small number at a time does seem to help with this.

00:45:15.300 --> 00:45:18.820
I think it's partly a matter of trust.

00:45:18.820 --> 00:45:23.020
I'm afraid I don't have anything more specific than that that I can recommend.

00:45:23.060 --> 00:45:27.379
I think people are going to become more comfortable in a hurry as we all start doing a lot more

00:45:27.379 --> 00:45:30.979
online in a hurry.

00:45:30.979 --> 00:45:35.060
Lynn Williams, how do you work with Google Docs and HackMD when it's new to your class

00:45:35.060 --> 00:45:37.580
and they've said its use is overwhelming?

00:45:37.580 --> 00:45:38.820
Really good question.

00:45:38.820 --> 00:45:41.219
I don't use it on day one.

00:45:41.219 --> 00:45:46.139
I will sometimes for instructor training because we've only got day one.

00:45:46.139 --> 00:45:51.219
But in a lot of other circumstances, I'm going to introduce these practices to people one

00:45:51.219 --> 00:45:55.060
at a time over the course of several lessons.

00:45:55.060 --> 00:45:59.500
First day, just get them used to using Zoom and taking turns speaking because that's the

00:45:59.500 --> 00:46:02.100
most important thing.

00:46:02.100 --> 00:46:07.179
Second class with them, get them used to the idea that when I ask a question, they can

00:46:07.179 --> 00:46:10.699
all give short responses in chat.

00:46:10.699 --> 00:46:11.899
It's not archived.

00:46:11.899 --> 00:46:13.139
It'll fly by.

00:46:13.139 --> 00:46:19.540
I probably don't even read all of them, but I'm getting them used to contributing.

00:46:19.540 --> 00:46:24.659
Things like a focus group, things like turning on their own video, things like using the

00:46:24.659 --> 00:46:29.540
Google Doc, lesson two, lesson three.

00:46:29.540 --> 00:46:33.500
Coming down a bit, how do you make sure each student is paying attention?

00:46:33.500 --> 00:46:34.500
You can't.

00:46:34.500 --> 00:46:36.179
And this is from Mateus.

00:46:36.179 --> 00:46:38.419
We can't do it in person either.

00:46:38.419 --> 00:46:43.500
I remember very clearly being in an electrical engineering class watching a colleague teach.

00:46:43.500 --> 00:46:48.260
And since I was standing at the back and looking down these rows of seats, I could see that

00:46:48.300 --> 00:46:53.500
almost a third of the students were playing poker online during the lecture.

00:46:53.500 --> 00:46:59.419
We're not going to do better than that when we shift them all online.

00:46:59.419 --> 00:47:06.100
What we can do is the best we can with the tools we have.

00:47:06.100 --> 00:47:10.459
Karina Marks, whereby.com, Skype for Business, Microsoft Teams.

00:47:10.459 --> 00:47:13.340
I like whereby.com a lot.

00:47:13.340 --> 00:47:18.100
For those of you who haven't seen it, it uses modern web standards like WebRTC.

00:47:18.100 --> 00:47:19.860
It's a beautiful little tool.

00:47:19.860 --> 00:47:23.899
I think Skype for Business is a really good advertisement for Zoom.

00:47:23.899 --> 00:47:29.139
I was on a Skype call Tuesday night for the first time in ages with my guitar teacher.

00:47:29.139 --> 00:47:31.060
And we're going to try Zoom next time.

00:47:31.060 --> 00:47:34.219
I haven't used Microsoft Teams.

00:47:34.219 --> 00:47:39.360
I'd be interested in other people's experience of using it as a teaching platform.

00:47:39.360 --> 00:47:42.340
Is there a way to help teach us how to use Zoom if we never have?

00:47:42.340 --> 00:47:43.540
From Michelle Connor.

00:47:43.540 --> 00:47:44.540
Okay.

00:47:44.540 --> 00:47:45.540
Mail me.

00:47:45.540 --> 00:47:47.340
I'm greg.wilson at rstudio.com.

00:47:47.340 --> 00:47:48.340
We'll set up a session.

00:47:48.340 --> 00:47:52.540
We'll show you what we know.

00:47:52.540 --> 00:47:57.860
Other recommended platforms for video calls from Marina Julias Cabezas.

00:47:57.860 --> 00:47:59.500
I'm in Toronto, Canada.

00:47:59.500 --> 00:48:01.060
I know what works here.

00:48:01.060 --> 00:48:05.100
I would be very grateful for comments from other people about what has worked where they

00:48:05.100 --> 00:48:07.300
are.

00:48:07.300 --> 00:48:12.300
I don't know what a good video conferencing solution is in Argentina or Malaysia or South

00:48:12.300 --> 00:48:13.540
Africa.

00:48:13.540 --> 00:48:17.459
I don't want to give you misleading information, but please, throw it into the RStudio Community

00:48:17.459 --> 00:48:20.459
channel or throw it to me and I'll share it.

00:48:20.459 --> 00:48:23.139
Why is dead air so bad?

00:48:23.139 --> 00:48:28.979
A couple of moments of quiet time after hearing a question is fine, but a couple of moments

00:48:28.979 --> 00:48:31.840
really does mean a couple of moments.

00:48:31.840 --> 00:48:43.179
People will become very uncomfortable with a silence like the one I just did, right?

00:48:43.179 --> 00:48:48.379
If they've got video and can see that you're still there, that reduces it a bit.

00:48:48.379 --> 00:48:55.139
But it is still uncomfortable to have a long pause.

00:48:55.139 --> 00:48:59.060
And Jeremiah is asking, these are great, but many ideas relate to live or asynchronous

00:48:59.060 --> 00:49:00.060
teaching.

00:49:00.060 --> 00:49:02.139
With my students scattered, this won't work.

00:49:02.139 --> 00:49:06.060
Any advice on making asynchronous teaching compelling?

00:49:06.060 --> 00:49:10.459
That one's actually easier to do online because you're already doing a lot of it.

00:49:10.459 --> 00:49:13.300
You're probably already publishing your slides.

00:49:13.300 --> 00:49:17.139
You're probably already using some sort of homework submission system.

00:49:17.139 --> 00:49:21.899
You probably, hopefully, already have some sort of discussion forum or board or mailing

00:49:21.899 --> 00:49:24.500
list set up for your class.

00:49:24.500 --> 00:49:26.939
That stuff won't change.

00:49:26.939 --> 00:49:34.000
If your administration is pushing you to record and publish videos on short notice, please

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:35.060
push back.

00:49:35.060 --> 00:49:36.860
It's a lot of work.

00:49:36.860 --> 00:49:41.659
If you're worried about burning up, particularly now that you're juggling everything else,

00:49:41.659 --> 00:49:43.899
that's going to be the one that breaks you.

00:49:43.899 --> 00:49:50.860
If you're already doing async teaching with text and images and static documents, that's

00:49:50.860 --> 00:49:53.860
the way you want to run.

00:49:53.860 --> 00:49:58.179
Leon Jesson, I could see it was online, and during the four-hour class, I lost some of

00:49:58.179 --> 00:49:59.860
the lower-tier students.

00:49:59.860 --> 00:50:05.899
So Leon, I would ask, did they drop out because it was a four-hour class?

00:50:05.939 --> 00:50:08.780
Four hours is a long time in one chunk.

00:50:08.780 --> 00:50:13.179
I mean, human attention is 45 to 90 minutes without a reset.

00:50:13.179 --> 00:50:17.899
I think if you're putting people into a four-hour class, you're going to lose people for a whole

00:50:17.899 --> 00:50:19.379
bunch of reasons.

00:50:19.379 --> 00:50:21.820
I couldn't do it these days because of my back.

00:50:21.820 --> 00:50:26.060
I simply can't sit in a chair for four hours at a go.

00:50:26.060 --> 00:50:30.699
The second question would be, when you say lower-tier, do you mean people who are less

00:50:30.699 --> 00:50:36.620
advanced, people who have less technical skill or have a less solid grasp of the material?

00:50:36.620 --> 00:50:40.899
In which case, they were checking out in your in-person class as well.

00:50:40.899 --> 00:50:43.020
It just wasn't as obvious.

00:50:43.020 --> 00:50:47.020
They were physically present, but mentally they had checked out, and now you're seeing

00:50:47.020 --> 00:50:48.020
it.

00:50:48.020 --> 00:50:53.820
And one of the things that we get from people logging out of Zoom, logging out of video

00:50:53.820 --> 00:50:58.060
calls, is that we can actually see who's checking out in a way that we couldn't before.

00:50:58.060 --> 00:51:00.100
It's not creating the problem necessarily.

00:51:00.100 --> 00:51:01.100
It's revealing it.

00:51:01.100 --> 00:51:05.300
And that may sound like I'm making an excuse or trying to explain it away.

00:51:05.300 --> 00:51:09.540
The honest truth is, I don't know, and I don't know of any research on this.

00:51:09.540 --> 00:51:14.739
Amadou Dikho, do you have any tips to notice quickly when you're losing someone during

00:51:14.739 --> 00:51:17.340
a training?

00:51:17.340 --> 00:51:21.219
Pair them up with them in groups as quickly as possible so that their peers can support

00:51:21.219 --> 00:51:22.219
them.

00:51:22.219 --> 00:51:26.300
Breakout rooms, pairwise discussions, having them review each other's work in a shared

00:51:26.300 --> 00:51:29.100
document, things like that.

00:51:29.100 --> 00:51:33.260
You can't give individual attention to a dozen people at once, never mind a class of

00:51:33.260 --> 00:51:34.540
50.

00:51:34.540 --> 00:51:36.899
They can give attention to each other.

00:51:36.899 --> 00:51:42.899
The one thing that you have to monitor is that they're not being trolls.

00:51:42.899 --> 00:51:48.780
Provided attendance is named, not anonymous, you've got some sort of control over that.

00:51:48.780 --> 00:51:54.179
But if you have 50 people anonymously in a classroom giving each other feedback, somebody's

00:51:54.179 --> 00:51:57.979
going to be rude to somebody, and then you've lost a learner.

00:51:57.979 --> 00:52:03.979
So I strongly prefer that people identify themselves, and I think since most of us are

00:52:03.979 --> 00:52:09.820
working in formal educational contexts, either university classroom or a paid training event,

00:52:09.820 --> 00:52:13.580
it's okay to ask for real names.

00:52:13.580 --> 00:52:18.020
Jeffrey Thompson, we're doing async instruction, recording short videos, have students watch

00:52:18.020 --> 00:52:20.820
them, and then holding virtual office hours.

00:52:20.820 --> 00:52:25.459
Great, this is the equivalent of a flipped classroom.

00:52:25.459 --> 00:52:29.820
A flipped classroom is one where the students learn the material out of class and do the

00:52:29.820 --> 00:52:34.699
homework in class so that when they're actually trying to apply the knowledge, you're right

00:52:34.699 --> 00:52:36.979
there with them when they need you most.

00:52:36.979 --> 00:52:43.340
Have them work through problems in that shared session.

00:52:43.340 --> 00:52:49.260
Ask one of them to share their screen and actually solve a small programming problem,

00:52:49.260 --> 00:52:53.620
or if they've got a tablet and a fingertip, to work out an equation there in front of

00:52:53.620 --> 00:52:54.620
people.

00:52:54.780 --> 00:52:58.659
You wouldn't bring somebody up and have them do work on a whiteboard in an in-person class.

00:52:58.659 --> 00:53:02.419
You would have somebody play a passage on a saxophone in a band class.

00:53:02.419 --> 00:53:08.219
You can do that to improve engagement and to take full advantage of the interactivity

00:53:08.219 --> 00:53:11.139
of those office hours.

00:53:11.139 --> 00:53:18.739
Skipping down again, tips for engaging when there are many, many students.

00:53:18.739 --> 00:53:23.860
All right, something I should have emphasized more during the presentation, you are not

00:53:23.899 --> 00:53:29.780
going to be able to do better in the next three months shifting online than you're doing

00:53:29.780 --> 00:53:33.379
right now in person.

00:53:33.379 --> 00:53:38.500
One person lecturing to a class of 1,000 is a poor learning experience.

00:53:38.500 --> 00:53:40.979
It doesn't matter if it's online or not.

00:53:40.979 --> 00:53:45.540
Peer instruction goes a long way towards addressing that, right?

00:53:45.540 --> 00:53:48.820
Getting them talking to each other in small groups periodically to clear up each other's

00:53:48.820 --> 00:53:53.100
misconceptions is a proven scalable approach to this.

00:53:53.340 --> 00:53:57.500
But if you're trying to take broadcast instruction where you're the one delivering information

00:53:57.500 --> 00:54:02.699
to all of them, in an in-person class, a lot of them aren't engaged and a lot of them are

00:54:02.699 --> 00:54:05.260
lost, you just don't realize it.

00:54:05.260 --> 00:54:08.699
So we're not going to be able to do better right away.

00:54:08.699 --> 00:54:14.219
My goal for the next 90 days is just not to do worse.

00:54:14.219 --> 00:54:21.260
Coming down to a couple of others because we're almost out of time, excuse me.

00:54:21.260 --> 00:54:25.260
Some more questions about async teaching.

00:54:25.260 --> 00:54:30.219
Can you talk about adding captions to live-streamed content on Zoom?

00:54:30.219 --> 00:54:31.860
Absolutely.

00:54:31.860 --> 00:54:39.739
I add speaker's notes to the slide deck rather than captioning the live-streamed content

00:54:39.739 --> 00:54:43.300
because I find that's easier for people to search.

00:54:43.300 --> 00:54:48.820
I don't have a lot of experience with adding captions to live-streamed content.

00:54:48.820 --> 00:54:52.739
If you can throw that question to me by email, I'll go and find somebody who's done this

00:54:52.739 --> 00:54:58.580
more than I have, and we will come back and give you an answer.

00:54:58.580 --> 00:55:04.739
Lisa Johnson, any advice for sticky note substitutions for participants to give feedback on the pace?

00:55:04.739 --> 00:55:09.780
For those of you who don't know, a trick pioneered in the Carpentries workshops is to give everybody

00:55:09.780 --> 00:55:12.020
a green sticky and a red sticky.

00:55:12.020 --> 00:55:13.899
Green sticky means things are going okay.

00:55:13.899 --> 00:55:17.860
Red sticky means I've got a problem, I need help.

00:55:17.860 --> 00:55:24.979
In Zoom, people can set an icon, thumbs up, thumbs down, you know, how am I feeling about this right now?

00:55:24.979 --> 00:55:30.419
It's kind of hard for you as the teacher to monitor those, so that's something your co-pilot can do.

00:55:30.419 --> 00:55:37.219
I wish there were better controls or something a little more adaptive to indicate, but you

00:55:37.219 --> 00:55:39.659
can use thumbs up, thumbs down in Zoom.

00:55:39.659 --> 00:55:46.459
I don't know if there's a similar capability in GoToMeeting, GoToWebinar rather.

00:55:46.459 --> 00:55:54.620
Going down a little further, software for online teaching, pick a video conferencing

00:55:54.620 --> 00:56:00.699
tool, pick a wiki tool or use Google Docs, pick something for real-time chat.

00:56:00.699 --> 00:56:03.659
It can be Slack or anything else.

00:56:03.659 --> 00:56:07.699
I don't recommend any of the custom integrated tools.

00:56:07.699 --> 00:56:12.419
Most learning management systems are actually grading management systems that don't really

00:56:12.419 --> 00:56:16.139
help with the learning and the interactive experience.

00:56:16.139 --> 00:56:19.620
Lisa Johnson, do you have audio tips?

00:56:19.620 --> 00:56:24.100
The tips for audio issues where more than one student has something to say at the same time.

00:56:24.100 --> 00:56:28.300
Mute everybody and then you invite somebody into the conversation.

00:56:28.300 --> 00:56:32.300
Parliamentary rules, nobody speaks unless the speaker calls on them.

00:56:32.300 --> 00:56:37.500
When you're doing that, your job as the teacher becomes that as more of a traffic director.

00:56:37.500 --> 00:56:41.939
You're deciding who speaks next and why.

00:56:41.939 --> 00:56:44.820
It doesn't take very long for people to get used to it.

00:56:44.820 --> 00:56:48.899
And if you're proactive about muting everybody, they'll pretty quickly learn that they're

00:56:48.899 --> 00:56:51.540
not going to be allowed to break that rule.

00:56:51.540 --> 00:56:54.340
How do you deal with trolls?

00:56:54.340 --> 00:56:56.739
Sudhir Shukla.

00:56:56.739 --> 00:56:58.300
Really important question.

00:56:58.300 --> 00:57:03.020
You deal with them the same way that you would in an in-person class.

00:57:03.020 --> 00:57:06.979
You start by reminding everybody that there is a code of conduct and certain rules are

00:57:06.979 --> 00:57:09.300
expected to be followed.

00:57:09.300 --> 00:57:11.739
Everybody gets one warning.

00:57:11.739 --> 00:57:15.139
They may not understand that they've transgressed.

00:57:15.139 --> 00:57:18.860
After that, yes, absolutely, shut them down.

00:57:18.860 --> 00:57:21.020
Mute them and leave them muted.

00:57:21.020 --> 00:57:23.100
Disable their access to the doc.

00:57:23.100 --> 00:57:28.060
I recommend that you don't kick them out of the room so that they're unable to see your

00:57:28.060 --> 00:57:32.739
presentation because then they might go and complain to somebody.

00:57:32.739 --> 00:57:38.500
But take away their ability to impede other people's learning experience.

00:57:38.540 --> 00:57:43.139
As soon as somebody's a troll, your responsibility is no longer to them.

00:57:43.139 --> 00:57:44.659
It's to all of your other learners.

